data.content:
Yes! Since your test data is all constants, use `[DataRow]` for inline, type-safe data:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **computed/non-constant data**, keep `DynamicData` but use tuples instead of `object[]` for type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**

| Approach | Best for | Type-safe | Requires constants |
|---|---|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Simple inline values | ✅ | Yes |
| `DynamicData` + tuples | Computed/complex data | ✅ | No |
| `DynamicData` + `object[]` | Legacy code | ❌ | No |

`[DataRow]` is the cleanest here. The tuple-based `DynamicData` approach (requires **MSTest v3.8+**) is better when you need runtime-generated data or complex objects that can't be attribute parameters.
